{{Jurassic}} The '''Hettangian''' is the earliest [[age (geology)|age]] and lowest [[stage (stratigraphy)|stage]] of the [[Jurassic]] [[Geological time scale|period]] of the [[geologic timescale]]. It spans the time between 201.3 ± 0.2 [[annum|Ma]] and 199.3 ± 0.3 Ma (million years ago).<ref name="benton, 2012">{{cite book|last=Benton|first=Michael J.|title=Prehistoric Life|year=2012|publisher=Dorling Kindersley|location=Edinburgh, Scotland|isbn=978-0-7566-9910-9|pages=44–45}}</ref> The Hettangian follows the [[Rhaetian]] (part of the [[Triassic]] period) and is followed by the [[Sinemurian]].<ref>For a detailed geologic timescale, see Gradstein ''et al.'' (2004)</ref>
In European stratigraphy the Hettangian is a part of the time span in which the [[Lias Group|Lias]] was deposited. An example is the British [[Blue Lias]], which has an upper Rhaetian to Sinemurian age. Another example is the lower Lias from the [[Northern Limestone Alps]] where well-preserved but very rare ammonites, including [[Alsatites]], have been found.
==Stratigraphic definitions== The Hettangian was introduced in the literature by Swiss palaeontologist, [[Eugène Renevier]], in 1864. The stage takes its name from [[Hettange-Grande]], a town in north-eastern [[France]], just south of the border with [[Luxembourg]] on the main road from [[Luxembourg City]] to [[Metz]].
The base of the Hettangian stage (which is also the base of the Lower Jurassic [[series (stratigraphy)|series]] and the entire Jurassic [[system (stratigraphy)|system]]) is defined as the place in the stratigraphic column where fossils of the [[ammonite]] [[genus]] ''[[Psiloceras]]'' first appear. A global reference profile (a [[GSSP]]) for the base was defined 2010 at the [[Kuhjoch]] in the [[Karwendel]] in western [[Austria]].<ref>[http://www.stratigraphy.org/GSSP/index.html GSSP Table] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121115175854/http://www.stratigraphy.org/GSSP/index.html |date=2012-11-15 }}</ref> The top of the Hettangian stage (the base of the Sinemurian) is at the first appearances of ammonite [[genus|genera]] ''[[Vermiceras]]'' and ''[[Metophioceras]]''.
===Biostratigraphy=== The Hettangian contains three ammonite [[biozone]]s in the [[Tethys Ocean|Tethys domain]]: *zone of ''[[Schlotheimia|Schlotheimia angulata]]'' *zone of ''[[Alsatites|Alsatites liasicus]]'' *zone of ''[[Psiloceras|Psiloceras planorbis]]''
==Palaeontology==
===†Ammonites=== [[File:Alsatites proaries SAM 0425.JPG|thumb|''Alsatites proaries'']]
At the end of the Triassic period, the ammonites died out almost entirely. During the Hettangian, however, the "Neoammonites" developed relatively quickly, so that even in the middle Hettangian a large number of genera and species existed.
